// Boating-licence question bank — GIFT export for Moodle.
// Self-contained: figures are embedded as base64 data URIs.

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Signalisation des voies et des bateaux

::q-fr-cevni-47-fc5e54b6:: [html]On an inland waterway, what does ONE prolonged blast from a vessel generally mean? {
=“Attention”
~“I am turning around”
~“I am stopped”
####[html]One prolonged blast is the “Attention” signal; it draws other vessels' attention.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://unece.org/transport/inland-water-transport">CEVNI — signal général « Attention » (un son prolongé) — CEVNI — Code européen des voies de navigation intérieure (CEE-ONU, Résolution n° 24)</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Réglementation, permis et radio

::q-fr-codetransports-58-ce87c1b3:: [html]Driving a boat under the influence of alcohol is\: {
=Prohibited
~Allowed on canals
~Tolerated at night
####[html]Prohibited\: the skipper must be fit to steer and react, as when driving a vehicle.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/texte_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/">Code des transports, art. L.4274-14 — conduite en état alcoolique (≥ 0,5 g/L) — Code des transports — navigation intérieure (titre de navigation, alcoolémie, règlements particuliers de police)</a>
}

::q-fr-codetransports-76-9ac86898:: [html]Which document, specific to the boat, must be available aboard on inland waters? {
=The boat's circulation card
~A road map of the area
~Only the engine manual
####[html]The boat's circulation card (navigation title), together with, where applicable, the driver's licence and proof of insurance.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/texte_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/">Code des transports, art. L.4221-1 — titre de navigation (carte de circulation) — Code des transports — navigation intérieure (titre de navigation, alcoolémie, règlements particuliers de police)</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Protection de l'environnement

::q-fr-codetransports-78-6de9f8e6:: [html]What should the boater do with waste water (black water) on inland waters? {
=Hold it in a tank and empty it ashore
~Discharge it discreetly at night
~Discharge it far from the banks
####[html]Keep it in a holding tank aboard, then empty it at shore collection facilities; discharging it into the waterway is prohibited.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/texte_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/">Code des transports, art. R.4241-63 / CDNI (décret 2010-197) — eaux usées (cuve, dépôt à terre) — Code des transports — navigation intérieure (titre de navigation, alcoolémie, règlements particuliers de police)</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Réglementation, permis et radio

::q-fr-decret2007-100-0968258d:: [html]From what age may a person not holding a driving title take part in introductory training to operate motorised watercraft? {
=Over sixteen years of age
~Over eighteen years of age
~Over fourteen years of age
####[html]The text reserves introductory training in operating motorised watercraft, as well as supervised touring led by a qualified instructor, to persons over sixteen years of age who do not hold a driving title, both in maritime and inland waters.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/jorf/article_jo/LEGIARTI000006885162">Décret 2007-1167, art. 10 — Décret n° 2007-1167 du 2 août 2007 relatif au permis de conduire des bateaux de plaisance à moteur</a>
}

::q-fr-decret2007-101-b108f641:: [html]On the inland waterways and bodies of water listed by the minister, on what condition is the driver of a chartered houseboat exempt from the recreational-boat driving licence? {
=When holding a houseboat driving certificate issued in accordance with the provisions set by the minister
~When the houseboat's length is less than fifteen metres
~When accompanied by a holder of the recreational licence with the inland-waters endorsement
####[html]The text exempts the driver of a chartered houseboat from the licence when holding a houseboat driving certificate issued in accordance with provisions set by the minister responsible for transport, on the waterways and bodies of water whose list is set by that minister.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/jorf/article_jo/LEGIARTI000006885164">Décret 2007-1167, art. 11 — Décret n° 2007-1167 du 2 août 2007 relatif au permis de conduire des bateaux de plaisance à moteur</a>
}

::q-fr-decret2007-56-ff63a4eb:: [html]What licence is needed to drive a motor pleasure boat over 4.5 kW on rivers and canals? {
=The permis plaisance inland-waters option
~No licence is needed
~The côtière option always suffices
####[html]The permis plaisance “eaux intérieures” option (the côtière option is for the sea).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/loda/id/JORFTEXT000000648362/">Décret n° 2007-1167 du 2 août 2007, art. 2 — option eaux intérieures — Décret n° 2007-1167 du 2 août 2007 relatif au permis de conduire des bateaux de plaisance à moteur</a>
}

::q-fr-decret2007-99-bd691bcb:: [html]How is a "recreational craft" (bateau de plaisance) defined? {
=Any boat or ship, whatever its type or mode of propulsion, intended for leisure or sport purposes
~Only a motorised boat intended for leisure or sport purposes
~Any boat under 20 metres used to carry passengers on a commercial basis
####[html]Under the definitions given, a "recreational craft" means any boat or ship, whatever its type or mode of propulsion, intended to be used for leisure or sport purposes. The definition sets no condition as to motorisation or size.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/jorf/article_jo/LEGIARTI000006266726">Décret 2007-1167, art. 1 — Décret n° 2007-1167 du 2 août 2007 relatif au permis de conduire des bateaux de plaisance à moteur</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Sécurité et matériel d'armement

::q-fr-division245-114-303d94ff:: [html]This order applies in particular to vessels whose hull length falls within which range? {
=Greater than or equal to 2.50 metres and less than 20 metres
~Greater than or equal to 5 metres and less than 24 metres
~Less than 2.50 metres only
####[html]The text applies to vessels with a hull length greater than or equal to 2.50 metres and less than 20 metres (and whose length × beam × draught product is under 100 cubic metres).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/jorf/article_jo/LEGIARTI000032045426">Division 245, art. 1 — Division 245 (arrêté du 10 février 2016) — matériel d'armement et de sécurité des bateaux de plaisance en eaux intérieures</a>
}

::q-fr-division245-115-ffb74065:: [html]To use a hydrofoil-propelled craft on inland waters (other than lakes and closed bodies of water), what condition must the user meet? {
=Hold the recreational licence with the inland-waters endorsement, or be accompanied by a holder of that licence
~Navigate exclusively at night, with a marker light switched on
~Hold the recreational licence with the coastal endorsement, the inland-waters endorsement never being required
####[html]The text provides that on inland waters the user holds the recreational licence with the inland-waters endorsement, or else is accompanied by a holder of that licence. Night use is excluded because these craft operate only in daytime, and the inland-waters endorsement is waived only on lakes and closed bodies of water.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/jorf/article_jo/LEGIARTI000032045436">Division 245, art. 11 — Division 245 (arrêté du 10 février 2016) — matériel d'armement et de sécurité des bateaux de plaisance en eaux intérieures</a>
}

::q-fr-division245-53-87ddd9c0:: [html]Aboard a small craft on inland waters, what must each person have? {
=A personal flotation device
~A compulsory drysuit
~Nothing, if they can swim
####[html]Every person aboard must have a suitable personal flotation device (lifejacket / buoyancy aid).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/loda/id/JORFTEXT000032036538/">Arrêté du 10 février 2016 (Division 245), art. 5 — EIF par personne (eaux intérieures) — Division 245 (arrêté du 10 février 2016) — matériel d'armement et de sécurité des bateaux de plaisance en eaux intérieures</a>
}

::q-fr-division245-74-61c84140:: [html]Among the useful equipment aboard a small craft, you must have a means of\: {
=Bailing the boat out (scoop or pump)
~Measuring the channel depth
~Recharging the VHF
####[html]Bailing the boat out (scoop, pump or bucket) if water comes in, in addition to the personal flotation devices.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/loda/id/JORFTEXT000032036538/">Arrêté du 10 février 2016 (Division 245), art. 5 — dispositif d'assèchement — Division 245 (arrêté du 10 février 2016) — matériel d'armement et de sécurité des bateaux de plaisance en eaux intérieures</a>
}

::q-fr-division245-75-641fbe2b:: [html]To be able to stop safely away from a quay, a craft must have\: {
=An anchor with its rode
~A second engine
~A liferaft
####[html]A suitable means of anchoring (an anchor with its line) to hold the boat.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/loda/id/JORFTEXT000032036538/">Arrêté du 10 février 2016 (Division 245), art. 6 — ligne de mouillage — Division 245 (arrêté du 10 février 2016) — matériel d'armement et de sécurité des bateaux de plaisance en eaux intérieures</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Réglementation, permis et radio

::q-fr-iturr-77-446e0b94:: [html]To use a VHF radio aboard, the skipper must, as a rule, hold\: {
=The restricted radiotelephone certificate (CRR)
~The boat licence alone
~No particular certificate
####[html]The restricted radiotelephone certificate (CRR), which authorises the use of a VHF. Since 2011 it is no longer required in French territorial waters for a hand-held VHF without DSC; it remains required for a fixed or DSC-equipped VHF and for navigating abroad.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.itu.int/pub/R-REG-RR">UIT, Règlement des radiocommunications, art. 47 — certificat d'opérateur (CRR, délivré par l'ANFR) — UIT — Règlement des radiocommunications (canaux VHF maritimes, procédures de détresse et d'urgence)</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Règles de barre et de route

::q-fr-rgp-102-05aeeaee:: [html]Under what condition may an overtaking vessel begin to overtake? {
=Only after making sure that the manoeuvre can be carried out without danger.
~Only after receiving explicit permission from the vessel being overtaken.
~As soon as the vessel being overtaken has reduced its speed.
####[html]The text provides that overtaking is permitted only if the overtaking vessel has made sure that the manoeuvre can be carried out without danger. The responsibility to verify safety thus lies with the overtaking vessel before starting the manoeuvre.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909233">RGP, art. A4241-53-10 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-103-ab66f03e:: [html]On a stretch where the course to follow is imposed by signs, what obligation applies to upstream-bound vessels with regard to downstream-bound vessels? {
=They must in no case impede downstream-bound vessels and must if necessary slow down or stop.
~They have priority and downstream-bound vessels must keep clear to let them pass.
~They must sound a prolonged blast before crossing the channel.
####[html]The text provides that, in such stretches, upstream-bound vessels must in no case impede the progress of downstream-bound vessels; in particular, where they have to cross the channel, they must if necessary reduce speed or stop to let downstream-bound vessels complete their manoeuvre.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909241">RGP, art. A4241-53-13 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-104-4a1635f6:: [html]Except when overtaking or passing, what is the minimum distance a vessel may approach a pushed convoy carrying the dangerous-goods marking? {
=No closer than 50 m.
~No closer than 10 m.
~No closer than 100 m.
####[html]The text prohibits navigating, except when overtaking or passing, closer than 50 m to a vessel, side-by-side formation or pushed convoy carrying the marking prescribed for the carriage of dangerous goods.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909251">RGP, art. A4241-53-18 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-105-121e7ae5:: [html]What does the basic rule provide concerning anchors, cables or chains during navigation? {
=In principle, it is prohibited to let them drag.
~It is always permitted to let them drag in order to slow the vessel down.
~It is mandatory to let them drag when drifting.
####[html]The text lays down the principle that it is prohibited to let anchors, cables or chains drag. This prohibition has exceptions (manoeuvres, small movements, authorised drifting, etc.), but the basic rule is indeed the prohibition on letting them drag.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909253">RGP, art. A4241-53-19 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-106-fc741ab6:: [html]What obligation applies to high-speed craft with respect to other vessels? {
=They must leave other vessels the space needed to keep their course and to manoeuvre, and may not require those vessels to keep out of their way.
~They have right of way and other vessels must keep clear of their course.
~They may require other vessels to reduce speed as they approach.
####[html]The text states that high-speed craft must leave other vessels the space needed to keep their course and to manoeuvre, and that they may not require those vessels to keep out of their way. They therefore have no right of way and must themselves leave the necessary space.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909213">RGP, art. A4241-53-2 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-107-9871dea7:: [html]How should a vessel that drifts downstream bow-pointed upstream with its engine running ahead be regarded? {
=As a vessel proceeding upstream, not as drifting.
~As a drifting vessel, and therefore in breach of the rules.
~As a vessel proceeding downstream required to give way.
####[html]The text in principle prohibits drifting, but specifies that vessels descending bow-pointed upstream with their engine running ahead are regarded as proceeding upstream, not as drifting.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909255">RGP, art. A4241-53-20 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-108-95f02556:: [html]Under what condition may a ferry begin to cross the inland waterway? {
=Only after making sure the crossing can be made without danger and without forcing other vessels to make a sudden change in course or speed.
~At any time, since ferries always have right of way over other vessels when crossing.
~Only after sounding one prolonged blast to warn all approaching vessels.
####[html]The text states that ferries may cross only after making sure that the movement of other vessels allows the crossing to be made without danger and without forcing those other vessels to make a sudden change in their course or speed.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909267">RGP, art. A4241-53-25 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-109-7912184c:: [html]What minimum distance must a vessel keep from the stern of a vessel showing the signals for mine-clearance operations? {
=Not within 1,000 m of its stern.
~Not within 100 m of its stern.
~Not within 500 m of its stern.
####[html]The text requires that vessels must not approach within 1,000 m of the stern of a vessel showing the signals for vessels engaged in mine-clearance. The minimum distance to be kept is therefore 1,000 m.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909354">RGP, art. A4241-53-37 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-110-fc5702dc:: [html]A boatmaster observes a risk of collision. What must he do? {
=Sound a series of very short blasts.
~Sound a single prolonged blast.
~Increase speed to clear the channel as quickly as possible.
####[html]The text states that any boatmaster who observes a risk of collision must sound a series of very short blasts. It also specifies that passing or overtaking is only allowed where the channel is unquestionably wide enough for simultaneous passage, and that vessels on courses excluding any risk of collision must not alter course or speed in a way that could create such a risk.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909219">RGP, art. A4241-53-4 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-111-b3619ec8:: [html]Regarding the vessel's speed, what obligation falls on the boatmaster? {
=Ensure a speed compatible with the characteristics of the waters and structures, neither below the minimum nor above the maximum limits set.
~Always maintain the maximum authorised speed to keep traffic flowing.
~Freely set his speed, as no minimum limit may ever be imposed on him.
####[html]The text requires the boatmaster to ensure that his vessel's speed is compatible with the characteristics of the inland waters and of the engineering structures; it may be neither below nor above the minimum or maximum speeds laid down by the special navigation police regulations.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232821">RGP, art. R4241-10 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-112-ad253f6c:: [html]A crew member temporarily determines the vessel's course and speed. What is his position with regard to the steering rules? {
=He is also responsible, to that extent, for compliance with the requirements imposed on the boatmaster.
~He bears no responsibility, the appointed boatmaster alone remaining liable.
~He becomes solely responsible, fully relieving the boatmaster.
####[html]The text provides that crew members and other persons on board who temporarily determine the vessel's course and speed are also responsible, to that extent, for compliance with the steering requirements imposed on the boatmaster.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232803">RGP, art. R4241-4 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-113-455df2f5:: [html]While the vessel is under way, where must the boatmaster be? {
=On board the vessel.
~Ashore, provided he keeps the vessel in sight.
~On board only when the vessel is actually moving.
####[html]The text states that while under way the boatmaster must be on board. It adds that the operator of a motorised floating appliance must also be on board whenever the appliance is at work, even if it is not moving, these provisions not applying to floating equipment.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232811">RGP, art. R4241-6 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Sécurité et matériel d'armement

::q-fr-rgp-116-a04cd5ec:: [html]What obligation applies to any person on board a vessel? {
=Comply with the orders given by the boatmaster in the interest of the safety of navigation and order on board.
~Obey the boatmaster only if she is part of the vessel's paid crew.
~Follow only the orders relating to boarding and disembarking.
####[html]Any person on board must comply with the orders given to them by the boatmaster in the interest of the safety of navigation and order on board.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232835">RGP, art. R4241-16 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-117-e91edabc:: [html]When a disaster (fire or incident) breaks out on board, what must the boatmaster do? {
=Take all necessary measures to control the incident and immediately notify the waterway manager or owner as well as the territorially competent CODIS.
~Wait for the rescue services to arrive before undertaking any action to fight the incident.
~Warn only the other vessels navigating nearby, without alerting any authority.
####[html]If a disaster breaks out on board, the boatmaster takes all foreseen and necessary measures to bring it under control and immediately notifies the competent manager or owner of the inland waterway as well as the territorially competent departmental operational fire and rescue centre (CODIS).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232839">RGP, art. R4241-18 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-118-9d0ffebb:: [html]Regarding raised anchors and objects protruding from the sides of a vessel, which rule applies? {
=No object liable to compromise safety may protrude from the sides, and raised anchors must not extend below the bottom or keel of the vessel.
~Objects may protrude from the sides provided they are marked by a flag during the day.
~Raised anchors must stay above the waterline but may extend below the keel of the vessel.
####[html]It is prohibited to let objects protrude from the sides of the vessel that could compromise the safety of other users, structures or installations; moreover, raised anchors must not extend below the bottom or keel of the vessel or below the lower plane of floating equipment.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232841">RGP, art. R4241-19 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-119-8c3afbe0:: [html]When a vessel runs aground or sinks, what is the obligation of its boatmaster? {
=Immediately notify the navigation policing authority and the waterway manager, and endeavour to clear the waterway in case of obstruction.
~Notify the authorities only if the vessel is carrying dangerous goods.
~Leave the vessel in place and wait for the manager's mandatory intervention without acting.
####[html]When a vessel is aground or sunk, its boatmaster immediately notifies the navigation policing authority and the waterway manager; if the vessel creates or may create a total or partial obstruction, the boatmaster must endeavour to have the waterway cleared as quickly as possible.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232851">RGP, art. R4241-24 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-120-9c897c89:: [html]What obligation rests on a boatmaster during periods of ice or flooding? {
=Strengthen his vessel's mooring lines, the ice being broken around the waterline by him or under his responsibility.
~Completely detach the vessel from the bank to let it drift freely with the ice.
~Mandatorily entrust the ice-breaking to the waterway manager, never to the boatmaster.
####[html]During periods of ice or flooding, the boatmaster strengthens his vessel's mooring lines; the ice is broken around the waterline by the boatmaster or under his responsibility.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232853">RGP, art. R4241-25 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Signalisation des voies et des bateaux

::q-fr-rgp-121-cabcb6ac:: [html]By day, what signal must a ferry not navigating freely display? {
=A green balloon placed at a height of at least 5 m
~A green cone, point downwards, placed at least 3 m high
~A bright green light visible from all sides
####[html]The text provides that, by day, ferries not navigating freely carry a green balloon placed at a height of at least 5 m. The other answers confuse this daytime signal with night lights or a non-existent mark.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027908960">RGP, art. A4241-48-16 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-122-99cf67d0:: [html]Unless otherwise prescribed, what characteristic must the prescribed signalling lights display? {
=A continuous and uniform light
~A regularly flashing light
~A light whose colour changes depending on direction
####[html]The text states that, unless otherwise prescribed, the prescribed lights must show a continuous and uniform light. Options proposing a flashing or colour-changing light do not match this requirement.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000039023130">RGP, art. A4241-48-2 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-123-00917e02:: [html]Unless otherwise prescribed, what shape must the panels and flags required by the on-board signalling rules have? {
=Rectangular
~Triangular
~Circular
####[html]Unless otherwise prescribed, the required panels and flags must be rectangular; their colours must be neither faded nor soiled, and their dimensions sufficient to ensure good visibility.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027908932">RGP, art. A4241-48-3 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-124-890f5e9e:: [html]Among the following visual means, which is NOT provided for a vessel in distress to call for help? {
=A yellow flag hoisted at the masthead
~Rockets or shells throwing red stars fired one at a time at short intervals
~A light signal made up of the group ...---... (SOS) in Morse code
####[html]The text lists, among others, a flag waved in a circular motion, rockets throwing red stars, and a light signal made up of the SOS group in Morse code. It does not mention a yellow flag hoisted at the masthead, which is therefore not among the authorised distress signals.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027908992">RGP, art. A4241-48-30 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-125-d4b7bdcc:: [html]For a signalling cylinder to be considered sufficiently visible, what minimum dimensions must it have? {
=A height of at least 0.80 m and a diameter of at least 0.50 m
~A height of at least 0.60 m and a diameter of at least 0.60 m
~A height of at least 1.00 m and a diameter of at least 0.80 m
####[html]The text specifies that the good-visibility condition is met when cylinders have a height of at least 0.80 m and a diameter of at least 0.50 m. The other figures proposed relate to different shapes or do not appear in the article.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027908934">RGP, art. A4241-48-4 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-126-d04ea8f2:: [html]Under what condition is the use of lights or signals other than those provided for by the signalling rules permitted? {
=For communication between vessels or between vessels and the shore, provided they cannot be confused with the lights or signals mentioned
~Only at night and after authorisation from the authority responsible for navigation policing
~For any use, as long as the vessel is moored
####[html]The text generally forbids using lights or signals other than those mentioned, but permits, for communication between vessels or between a vessel and the shore, the use of other lights or signals provided they cannot be confused with those mentioned. The other answers add conditions not found in the text.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027908936">RGP, art. A4241-48-5 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-127-60ced3bb:: [html]When a prescribed signalling light fails to work, what must the operator do? {
=Replace it without delay with an emergency light
~Stop navigating until the light is permanently repaired
~Wait until the next port to report the failure, with no other measure
####[html]When a prescribed signalling light is not working, it must be replaced without delay by an emergency light; restoration of a light of the prescribed intensity must take place as quickly as possible.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027908938">RGP, art. A4241-48-6 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-128-f35e1e74:: [html]What does the regulation say about the use of lights, searchlights, panels, flags or pennants on board? {
=It is forbidden to use lights or objects liable to be confused with the regulatory lights and signals
~Any advertising lighting is allowed provided it is switched off at night
~Dazzling searchlights are permitted if they are aimed towards the bank
####[html]It is forbidden to use lights, searchlights, panels, flags or other objects liable to be confused with the regulatory lights or signals, to impair their visibility or to complicate their identification, as well as lights or searchlights producing dazzle that could endanger or hinder navigation.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027908940">RGP, art. A4241-48-7 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-129-dced25b3:: [html]You are operating a vessel that is not a small craft. What does the regulation require regarding the prescribed sound signals? {
=It must, when needed, use the prescribed sound signals.
~It may give these signals only when navigating at night.
~It is exempt from giving any prescribed sound signal.
####[html]Every vessel, except small craft, must when needed use the sound signals set out in chapter III of annex 4. For such vessels the giving of these signals is an obligation, not a mere option.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909182">RGP, art. A4241-49-2 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-130-4afba183:: [html]Under what condition is the use of sound signals other than the prescribed ones permitted between vessels or between a vessel and the shore? {
=Provided they cannot be confused with the prescribed signals.
~Provided they are given only when approaching a lock.
~Provided they are louder than the prescribed signals.
####[html]Using sound signals other than the prescribed ones is forbidden, except, for communication between vessels or between a vessel and the shore, provided they cannot be confused with the prescribed signals.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909184">RGP, art. A4241-49-3 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-131-1634d529:: [html]To call for help, what sound signal may a vessel in distress give? {
=Bell peals or repeated prolonged blasts
~A single short blast followed by a one-minute silence
~Three short blasts given only once
####[html]A vessel in distress wishing to call for help may sound bell peals or repeated prolonged blasts; these signals replace or supplement the visual distress signals.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909186">RGP, art. A4241-49-4 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-132-3559d3da:: [html]Where are the prohibition, mandatory, restriction, recommendation and information signs of the inland waterway, together with their meaning, defined? {
=In annex 5.
~In annex 7.
~In annex 8.
####[html]It is annex 5 that defines the prohibition, mandatory, restriction, recommendation and information signs, as well as the auxiliary signs of the inland waterway and their meaning; boatmasters must comply with them.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909199">RGP, art. A4241-51-1 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-133-66108b3f:: [html]Where are the buoyage rules applicable on the inland waterway, upstream of the first obstacle to seagoing-vessel navigation, defined? {
=In annex 8.
~In annex 5.
~In annex 4.
####[html]It is annex 8 that defines the buoyage rules applying upstream of the first obstacle to seagoing-vessel navigation and that specifies under what conditions the various buoyage marks are used.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909202">RGP, art. A4241-51-2 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-134-1f313b87:: [html]Regarding equipment, what obligation applies to vessels, except for small craft? {
=Be equipped with a radiotelephone installation
~Carry a navigation radar device as a requirement
~Have an automatic identification system (AIS) in all circumstances
####[html]All vessels must carry a device enabling them to give sound signals; in addition, vessels, except for small craft, must be equipped with a radiotelephone installation.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000038225665">RGP, art. R4241-49 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-135-f5c164ad:: [html]In what case is the use of a navigation radar device mandatory for a vessel? {
=For certain vessels or certain navigation situations determined by ministerial order
~For all vessels without exception as soon as they navigate at night
~Only for motorised small craft
####[html]The use of a navigation radar device is required, for safety reasons, for certain vessels or in certain navigation situations determined by order of the minister responsible for transport.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232919">RGP, art. R4241-50 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Voies navigables et stationnement

::q-fr-rgp-136-7a1bdac9:: [html]At a berthing area marked by sign B.12, what obligation applies to all vessels? {
=Connect to an operational shore-side electrical connection point to fully cover their electricity needs during the stay
~Switch off all electrical equipment and remain completely powered down during the stay
~Run their onboard generator to feed power into the shore network
####[html]At such areas, all vessels must connect to an operational shore-side electrical connection point so as to fully cover their electrical energy needs during the stay.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000039010767">RGP, art. A4241-54-10 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-137-70fdcb75:: [html]In a section where anchoring is generally prohibited by a special policing regulation, under what conditions may a vessel nonetheless anchor? {
=Only in the areas indicated by sign E.6, and on the side of the waterway where that sign is placed
~Anywhere in the section, provided the vessel is marked at night
~Only with the prior written authorisation of the manager
####[html]In sections where anchoring is generally prohibited by a special policing regulation, vessels may anchor only in the areas indicated by the authorisation sign E.6, and only on the side of the waterway where that sign is placed.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909506">RGP, art. A4241-54-3 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-138-0f5c1e8c:: [html]For mooring or warping, which of the following is a vessel NOT permitted to use? {
=A handrail or a metal ladder
~A mooring bollard provided for that purpose
~A mooring ring fitted on the quay
####[html]It is forbidden to use, for mooring or warping, trees, guardrails, posts, bollards (markers), columns, metal ladders, handrails, and any equipment not intended for mooring; a mooring bollard, by contrast, is equipment provided for that purpose.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909508">RGP, art. A4241-54-4 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-139-a7f2aaf1:: [html]At a berthing/parking area, absent any other instructions, how must vessels arrange themselves? {
=Side by side starting from the bank, on the side of the waterway where the sign is placed
~In a single row aligned along the middle of the channel
~Rafted together starting from the bank opposite the sign
####[html]Failing other instructions, vessels must berth side by side starting from the bank, on the side of the waterway where the sign is placed.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909510">RGP, art. A4241-54-5 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-140-2437cb96:: [html]At a berthing area where a special-berth indication sign (type E.5.4 to E.5.15) is set up, who may berth there? {
=Only the categories of vessel to which the sign applies, and only on the side of the waterway where the sign is placed.
~All vessels, on both sides of the waterway, with no category restriction.
~The categories of vessel covered by the sign, but on either side of the waterway indifferently.
####[html]The rules state that only the categories of vessel to which the sign applies may berth, and only on the side of the waterway where the sign is placed.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909512">RGP, art. A4241-54-6 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-141-f7611d7d:: [html]For a berthed vessel with no boatmaster aboard, who is responsible for setting up the required watch or supervision? {
=The owner, operator or other person running the vessel
~The authority in charge of navigation policing
~The manager of the harbour or berthing area
####[html]Where the vessel has no boatmaster, responsibility for putting this watch or supervision in place falls on the owner, operator or other person running the vessel.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909516">RGP, art. A4241-54-8 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-142-140fb597:: [html]What requirement must a vessel's loading meet with regard to visibility for steering? {
=The load must not extend the zone of direct or indirect non-visibility for steering the vessel.
~The load may reduce visibility as long as a lookout is posted at the bow of the vessel.
~The load must never exceed the height of the wheelhouse, regardless of visibility.
####[html]The load on board must not extend the zone of direct or indirect non-visibility required to steer the vessel, under conditions set by ministerial order.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232861">RGP, art. R4241-27 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-143-01be1c37:: [html]How must the master of a vessel respond to the specific orders given by the officials and agents in charge of navigation policing for the safety or good order of navigation? {
=He complies with the specific orders given for the safety or good order of navigation.
~He may refuse to comply if he considers his own course to have priority.
~He is required to comply only on maritime waterways, never on inland waterways.
####[html]The master complies with the specific orders given by these officials and agents for the safety or good order of navigation.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232891">RGP, art. R4241-39 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-144-0ce8afab:: [html]What obligation does the master of a vessel have towards the officials and agents in charge of navigation policing who record offences? {
=Give them the facilities needed to carry out their task of recording offences.
~Leave the scene immediately so as not to hinder their intervention.
~Provide assistance only if the agents first present him with a judicial warrant.
####[html]The master must give these officials and agents the facilities needed to enable them to carry out their task of recording offences.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232893">RGP, art. R4241-40 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-145-0342c54d:: [html]What must the master of a vessel do regarding the documents that must be kept on board? {
=Produce them upon any request by the agents in charge of navigation policing.
~Send them by post only, within eight days of the request.
~Produce them only to agents holding a written requisition from a judge.
####[html]Every master is required to produce the documents that must be on board upon any request by the agents in charge of navigation policing.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232895">RGP, art. R4241-41 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-40-d508050f:: [html]Under the inland navigation police regulation (RGP), what is a “small craft” (menue embarcation)? {
=A vessel under 20 metres
~Any vessel under 24 metres
~A vessel under 15 metres only
####[html]As a rule, a vessel with a hull length under 20 metres (excluding passenger vessels, tugs, etc.).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP (Code des transports, art. R.4000-2, 7°) — menue embarcation (< 20 m) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-41-9ea04935:: [html]Where is mooring (stopping) of a vessel generally prohibited on a waterway? {
=Under bridges and in narrow passages
~Along every fitted quay
~Nowhere — mooring is unrestricted
####[html]Mooring is forbidden where it hampers navigation (under bridges, in narrow passages) and wherever a sign prohibits it.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-54-2 — stationnement interdit (ponts, passages étroits) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-42-1f794b0d:: [html]To limit wash (the wake that erodes banks and rocks moored boats), what must the driver do near the banks? {
=Reduce speed
~Increase speed to pass quickly
~Hug the bank as close as possible
####[html]Reduce speed when approaching banks, harbours and moored boats, to limit the wash.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-21 — vitesse et batillage — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Écluses, barrages et ouvrages

::q-fr-rgp-43-e53f0eaf:: [html]At a lock entrance, what does a RED light mean? {
=Entry forbidden, you must wait
~Entry authorised
~Exit from the lock only
####[html]A single red light means “no entry”; wait. A green light authorises entry; two red lights mean the lock is out of service.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-31 §1 — feux d'écluse (rouge \= accès interdit) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-44-9193cab9:: [html]Which light authorises entry into a lock? {
=The green light
~The red light
~Two red lights
####[html]A green light authorises entry. Two red lights mean the lock is out of service.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-31 §1 — feu vert d'écluse (accès autorisé) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-45-45186bd5:: [html]In a lock chamber, how should you handle your lines during locking? {
=Tend and adjust them, never made fast to a fixed point
~Make them fast hard to a fixed cleat
~Remove all the lines
####[html]The water level changes\: tend the lines and pay out or take in as needed, never make them fast to a fixed point (risk of parting or listing).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-30/-31 — conduite dans le sas d'écluse — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Signalisation des voies et des bateaux

::q-fr-rgp-46-7ffa546c:: [html]On a waterway, what does a rectangular sign with a red border and a white horizontal bar mean? {
=No passage / no entry
~Obligation to stop and refuel
~Recommendation to slow down
####[html]It is a prohibition sign (type A.1)\: no entry / passage forbidden.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, annexe 5, panneau A.1 — interdiction de passer — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-48-43e11fe7:: [html]At night, a power-driven vessel underway on inland waters shows a light to port. What colour is it? {
=Red
~Green
~Yellow
####[html]As at sea\: port sidelight red, starboard green, plus a white masthead light and a sternlight.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-48-13 — feux des menues embarcations motorisées (bâbord rouge) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-49-92709847:: [html]At night, a vessel moored away from the bank, outside a harbour, most often shows\: {
=An all-round white light
~A flashing red light
~No light
####[html]An ordinary white light visible all round, to signal its presence to other vessels.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-48-20 — signalisation en stationnement (feu blanc) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Règles de barre et de route

::q-fr-rgp-50-30f74d5c:: [html]On inland waters, with respect to large vessels, ferries and vessels on a regular service, small craft (pleasure boats) must\: {
=Keep out of their way
~Hold their course, having priority
~Force them to stop
####[html]Small craft must leave the way clear for large vessels, ferries and convoys\: they keep out of their way.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-3 — menues embarcations s'écartent des grands bateaux et bacs — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-51-397ff43c:: [html]As a general rule on an inland waterway, to which side should a vessel keep? {
=To its right (starboard)
~To its left (port)
~In the middle of the channel
####[html]Each vessel keeps to its right (starboard) as a rule; vessels then pass port to port, unless signs indicate otherwise.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-6 §1 — venir sur tribord (croisement bâbord-bâbord) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-52-5f6a7405:: [html]In a narrow passage (under a bridge, a tight channel) where crossing is impossible, what must the driver do? {
=Make sure the passage is clear before entering
~Always enter first
~Speed up to force through
####[html]Make sure the passage is clear before entering and give way per the signs; on rivers priority goes to the down-bound vessel (going with the current).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-8 — passage étroit (priorité à l'avalant) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Sécurité et matériel d'armement

::q-fr-rgp-54-03dfc925:: [html]A vessel's identification mark (registration) must be\: {
=Displayed visibly and legibly on the hull
~Kept only in the boat's papers
~Optional for pleasure craft
####[html]It must be displayed visibly and legibly on the hull, so the vessel can be identified.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-47-1 — marque d'identification du bateau — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-55-1942c7d7:: [html]Before getting under way, what must the skipper check (duty of care)? {
=The boat's condition, the safety gear and the weather
~Only the fuel level
~Nothing — checks are the lock's job
####[html]Ensure the boat and engine are sound, the safety equipment is aboard, and the conditions (water level, weather) are suitable.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. R.4241-9/-10 — devoir général de prudence du conducteur — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Réglementation, permis et radio

::q-fr-rgp-57-acb1b55b:: [html]Besides the general police regulation (RGP), a particular waterway may also be governed by\: {
=A particular police regulation (RPP)
~The road traffic code alone
~No other rule
####[html]A particular police regulation (RPP) adapts the general rules to the local circumstances of a given waterway or reach.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">Code des transports, art. R.4241-31/-32 — règlement particulier de police (RPP) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Protection de l'environnement

::q-fr-rgp-59-32f112e9:: [html]On inland waters, discharging hydrocarbons, waste water or rubbish into the waterway is\: {
=Prohibited
~Allowed in small amounts
~Free outside harbours
####[html]Prohibited\: such discharges pollute the waterway and must be collected and disposed of in the proper facilities.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP (Code des transports, art. R.4241-62) — rejet d'hydrocarbures interdit — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-60-80fd925f:: [html]To limit bank erosion and disturbance to wildlife, the boater should above all\: {
=Reduce speed and wash near the banks
~Run at full speed in the centre
~Moor in the reed beds
####[html]Reduce speed and wash when approaching banks, reed beds and sensitive natural areas.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-21 — réduire vitesse et batillage près des berges — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Voies navigables et stationnement

::q-fr-rgp-61-0b480791:: [html]On inland waters, what is a “down-bound” (avalant) vessel? {
=A vessel going downstream
~A vessel going upstream
~A vessel stopped against the bank
####[html]A down-bound vessel goes with the current (downstream); an up-bound (montant) one goes against it. On rivers the down-bound vessel, less manoeuvrable, has priority.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-1 et -53-6 §2 — montant/avalant (priorité à l'avalant) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-62-3e9f3647:: [html]Along a river or canal, how is your position located? {
=By kilometre points (bank markers)
~By latitude and longitude alone
~By nautical miles
####[html]By kilometre points (PK), shown by markers or plates on the banks, counting the kilometres from the start of the waterway.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">Voie navigable — repérage par points kilométriques (PK) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-63-17514081:: [html]Before passing under a bridge or a power line, what must the driver check? {
=That the air draft is less than the available headroom
~That its speed is at maximum
~That its anchor is down
####[html]That the air draft (the boat's height above the water) is less than the available headroom, shown by the signs.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, annexe 5, panneau C.2 — hauteur libre limitée (tirant d'air) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Écluses, barrages et ouvrages

::q-fr-rgp-64-3d9c8ad0:: [html]At a lock, who sets the order and manner in which vessels enter? {
=The lock-keeper and the lock's signs
~The fastest vessel
~Each driver, freely
####[html]The lock-keeper (or the lock's signs / automatic system); follow their instructions and the lights.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-31 §4 et §12 — instructions de l'éclusier — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-65-223fd27d:: [html]At a lock, what do TWO red lights mean? {
=The lock is out of service
~Entry is immediately authorised
~Exit is compulsory
####[html]The lock is out of service / closed to navigation. A single red light means “wait”, and a green light authorises entry.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-31 §1(a) — deux feux rouges (écluse hors service) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Signalisation des voies et des bateaux

::q-fr-rgp-66-ae886700:: [html]On inland waters, how do you recognise a PROHIBITION sign? {
=By its red border
~By being entirely blue
~By a green triangular shape
####[html]Prohibition signs have a red border (often a white bar with red), like the “no entry” sign.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, annexe 5, section A — signaux d'interdiction (bord rouge) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-67-51ebf59c:: [html]What does a rectangular BLUE sign with a white symbol generally give? {
=Information / guidance
~An absolute prohibition
~An immediate danger
####[html]Blue rectangular signs give information (mooring allowed, ferry, service point, etc.).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, annexe 5, section E — signaux d'indication (bleus) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-68-e7601837:: [html]A square BLUE sign bearing a white letter “P” means\: {
=Mooring permitted
~Mooring prohibited
~Marina 1 km ahead
####[html]Mooring (berthing) is permitted at this spot.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, annexe 5, panneau E.5 — stationnement autorisé (P) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-69-a7ece36b:: [html]A red-bordered sign bearing a white arrow indicates\: {
=An obligation to follow the shown direction
~A mere recommendation
~A bathing area
####[html]It is a mandatory sign\: you must follow the direction (the side) shown by the arrow.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, annexe 5, panneau B.1 — obligation (suivre la flèche) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-70-c06c8fc1:: [html]A sign bearing a number (e.g. “3.50 m”) generally indicates\: {
=A limit on headroom, width or depth
~The distance to the next lock
~The waterway's number
####[html]A restriction\: for example the available headroom, width or depth (series C signs). A maximum speed is instead a mandatory sign (B.6).<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, annexe 5, section C — restriction (hauteur, largeur ou profondeur) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Règles de barre et de route

::q-fr-rgp-71-6fe61170:: [html]On a flowing river, when an up-bound and a down-bound vessel meet, which has priority? {
=The down-bound vessel
~The up-bound vessel
~The larger of the two vessels
####[html]The down-bound vessel (going with the current) has priority because it manoeuvres less easily; the up-bound vessel leaves it the way and the chosen side.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-6 §2 — priorité de l'avalant — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-72-c619375a:: [html]On still water, two power-driven vessels meet head-on. What do they do? {
=Each alters to starboard
~Each alters to port
~They both stop
####[html]Each alters to starboard (its right) so they pass port to port.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-6 §1 — rencontre (chacun sur tribord) — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-73-dc2077e7:: [html]On inland waters, on which side does a vessel normally overtake another? {
=On the port (left) side of the overtaken vessel
~Always on the starboard side
~By passing very close to it
####[html]As a rule on the port (left) side of the vessel being overtaken, once sure the manoeuvre is safe; the overtaking vessel keeps clear of the one overtaken.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP, art. A.4241-53-11 §1 — dépassement par bâbord — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Protection de l'environnement

::q-fr-rgp-79-0edde366:: [html]When refuelling, what precaution prevents water pollution? {
=Avoid any overflow (do not fill to the brim)
~Fill as fast as possible
~Rinse the tank with canal water
####[html]Refuel unhurriedly and do not fill to the brim (use a funnel, watch the level) to avoid any fuel spilling into the water.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/section_lc/LEGITEXT000023086525/LEGISCTA000027232795/">RGP (Code des transports, art. R.4241-62) — prévention de la pollution — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Écluses, barrages et ouvrages

::q-fr-rgp-92-6b727339:: [html]At a bridge or weir opening bearing prohibition sign A.10, where is navigation permitted? {
=Only in the space between the two panels making up the sign
~Anywhere in the opening, except in the centre of the channel
~Preferably between the two panels, but without prohibition elsewhere
####[html]When a bridge or weir opening bears the prohibition sign A.10, navigation is forbidden outside the space between the two panels making up that sign; it is therefore allowed only between those two panels.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909328">RGP, art. A4241-53-26 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-93-d38c6683:: [html]An opening of a fixed bridge is marked by one or more red lights. What must you conclude? {
=The opening is forbidden to navigation.
~The opening is recommended as the preferred passage in both directions.
~The opening is reserved for upbound boats only.
####[html]When certain openings of fixed bridges are indicated by one or more red lights (or the general prohibition signal A.1), those openings are forbidden to navigation.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909330">RGP, art. A4241-53-27 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-94-7badcac5:: [html]When a vessel holding a right of priority at locks approaches the lock lay-bys or is moored there, how must the other vessels behave? {
=They must facilitate its passage as much as possible
~They keep their turn according to order of arrival
~They must immediately leave the lock lay-by
####[html]When vessels holding a right of priority at locks approach the lock lay-bys or are moored there, the other vessels must facilitate their passage as much as possible.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909340">RGP, art. A4241-53-32 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-95-22baf33b:: [html]During normal navigation periods, what is the maximum duration for which the manager may exceptionally authorise a vessel to moor in lock lay-bys? {
=Ten days
~Three days
~Thirty days
####[html]The manager may exceptionally authorise mooring in lock lay-bys during normal navigation periods, provided this does not exceed a maximum of ten days.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027909518">RGP, art. A4241-54-9 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-96-a715abca:: [html]Regarding the footbridges and other appurtenances of locks and dams, which rule applies? {
=Standing and moving about on them is forbidden, unless they are arranged to serve as a public passage.
~One may stand on them freely, including on movable bridges during operation.
~Moving about on them is allowed provided one wears a personal flotation device.
####[html]It is forbidden to stand and move about on the footbridges and other appurtenances of locks and dams, unless they are arranged to serve as a public passage; it is also forbidden to stand on movable bridges during operation.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232977">RGP, art. R4241-71 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

$CATEGORY: Boating licence · Lake Geneva (EN)/Protection de l'environnement

::q-fr-rgp-97-0f361a41:: [html]A discharge from your boat of a substance liable to create a danger to navigation has occurred. What must you do? {
=Notify without delay the navigation police authority and the manager, indicating the nature and location of the discharge.
~Report nothing as long as the discharge does not fully obstruct the water section.
~Warn only the other boats by a sound signal, without notifying any authority.
####[html]Throwing or letting fall into inland waters an object or substance liable to create an obstruction or danger is forbidden; if such a discharge occurs from a boat, the conductor must notify without delay the navigation police authority and the waterway manager, indicating as exactly as possible the nature and location of the discharge.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232849">RGP, art. R4241-23 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}

::q-fr-rgp-98-579197de:: [html]Which document concerning waste oils must be kept on board a motorized boat? {
=A valid waste-oil control logbook, on board every motorized boat or floating craft (except small craft).
~A waste-oil control logbook, required only on board small craft.
~An annual oil-change certificate issued by the waterway manager.
####[html]A valid waste-oil control logbook must be kept on board every motorized boat or floating craft, except small craft.<br>Source \: <a href\="https\://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/codes/article_lc/LEGIARTI000027232961">RGP, art. R4241-65 — Règlement général de police de la navigation intérieure (RGP/RGPNI) — Code des transports, art. R. 4241-1 et s.</a>
}
